05447nam a22006495i 9781847422583DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20072007xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a9781847422583  a(DE-B1597)646790  a(OCoLC)250711492  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 7aSOC0250002bisacsh04a364.36094100aResearching Criminal Justice. Young people and 'risk' /ced. by Maggie Blyth, Enver Solomon, Kerry Baker. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (128 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aResearching Criminal Justice00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgements -- tNotes on contributors -- tIntroduction -- tRisk assessment and risk management: the right approach? -- tRisk in practice: systems and practitioner judgement -- tYoung people and violence: balancing public protection with meeting needs -- tMental health, risk and antisocial behaviour in young offenders: challenges and opportunities -- tSerious incidents in the youth justice system: management and accountability -- tWorking with young people in a culture of public protection -- tNever too early? Reflections on research and interventions for early developmental prevention of serious harm -- tConclusions0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlongside the current media public preoccupation with high-risk offenders, there has been a shift towards a greater focus on risk and public protection in UK criminal justice policy. Much of the academic debate has centered on the impact of the risk paradigm on adult offender management services; less attention has been given to the arena of youth justice and young adults. Yet, there are critical questions for both theory - are the principles of risk management the same when working with young people? - and practice - how can practitioners respond to those young people who cause serious harm to others? - that need to be considered. The distinguished contributors to Young people and 'risk' consider risk not only in terms of public protection but also in terms of young people's own vulnerability to being harmed (either by others or through self-inflicted behaviour). One of the report's key objectives is to explore the links between these two distinct, but related, aspects of risk. Maggie Blyth is a member of the Parole Board for England and Wales and independent chair of Nottingham City Youth Offending Team. She also works independently as a criminal justice consultant. Kerry Baker is a researcher in the Centre for Criminology at the University of Oxford and also a consultant to the Youth Justice Board on issues of assessment, risk and public protection. Enver Solomon is Deputy Director of the Centre for Crime and Justice Studies, an independent charity affiliated to the Law School at King's College London.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aJuvenile delinquentszGreat Britain. 0aJuvenile justice, Administration ofzGreat Britain. 0aProblem youthzGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBailey, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, Kerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, Kerry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBlyth, Maggie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlyth, Maggie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBoswell, Gwyneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurnett, Ros, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKemshall, Hazel, econtributor.4ctb4https: